Report No 1 Received from US Consumer Relations, Date 04-MAY-2015, Reference No: R063976030.
Suspect Drug: Mucinex Mini Melts Orange Creme (Guaifenesin; Dextromethorphan Hydrobromide). 
Dosing: Took 200mg every 12 hours on 03-MAY-2015 and 200mg on 04-MAY-2015.
Co-suspect drug: Tylenol.
Dosing: Took 1 time on 03-MAY-2015 and 1 time on 04-MAY-2015
Case reference number US-RB-076989-15 is a spontaneous case report sent by a consumer or other non health 
professional which refers to a female aged 11 years.
Reporter (Grandmother) stated that she gave her 11 year old grandchild the Mucinex Mini Melts Orange Creme 
through an unknown route for an unknown indication. She gave two yesterday (03-MAY-2015) morning, and two 
last night (03-MAY-2015), then two on 04-MAY-2015 morning again, total took 6. The reporter had also been giving 
her grandchild Tylenol at an unknown dosing for an unknown indication at 12pm yesterday (03-MAY-2015) and at 
6am on 04-MAY-2015 morning. Her grandchild started to have nose bleeds yesterday (03-MAY-2015) night around 
8pm. The nose bleeding did stop about five minutes after it started and had not occurred again. The reporter stated
that this was not the first time she used this product.
Drug Therapy: Mucinex Mini Melts Orange Creme.
The reaction was deemed serious by the company because it was classed as medically significant due to 
Epistaxis .
The reporter's causality for the case is Possible. The reporting consumer or other non health professional's clinical 
assessment for drug MUCINEX MINI MELTS ORANGE CREME [Guaifenesin; Dextromethorphan Hydrobromide] is
as follows: seriousness not provided with a relatedness of Possible.
The company's assessment for the case is serious, possible and unlisted.
No further information was available at the time of report. 
Outcome: Recovered / Resolved.
